  "prompt": "When and how did WWI start and end?",
  "response": "## When and How WWI Started and Ended:\n\n**Start:**\n\n*   **When:** July 28, 1914\n\n*   **How:** The assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary, heir to the Austro-Hungarian throne, on June 28, 1914, in Sarajevo, Bosnia (then part of Austria-Hungary), by Gavrilo Princip, a Serbian nationalist, was the spark that ignited the war.\n\n    *   Austria-Hungary, with Germany's support, issued an ultimatum to Serbia with demands that were impossible to fully meet.\n    *   Serbia partially accepted the ultimatum, but Austria-Hungary declared war on Serbia on July 28, 1914.\n    *   This declaration of war triggered a chain reaction of alliances and treaties:\n        *   Russia mobilized its forces to support Serbia.\n        *   Germany declared war on Russia on August 1, 1914, and on France (Russia's ally) on August 3, 1914.\n        *   Germany invaded neutral Belgium on August 4, 1914, to reach France, which prompted Great Britain to declare war on Germany the same day.\n\n**End:**\n\n*   **When:** November 11, 1918, at 11:00 AM (the \"eleventh hour of the eleventh day of the eleventh month\")\n\n*   **How:**\n\n    *   By 1918, the Central Powers (Germany, Austria-Hungary, Ottoman Empire, Bulgaria) were facing severe strains due to:\n        *   Depleted resources\n        *   Economic hardship\n        *   Growing internal unrest\n        *   The arrival of fresh U.S. troops on the side of the Allies (France, Great Britain, Russia, Italy, United States, etc.) tipped the balance.\n    *   A series of Allied offensives on the Western Front pushed back the German army.\n    *   The Ottoman Empire and Bulgaria surrendered in September 1918.\n    *   Austria-Hungary began to disintegrate, and it signed an armistice on November 3, 1918.\n    *   Faced with mutiny at home and the collapse of its allies, Germany requested an armistice.\n    *   **The armistice, which effectively ended the fighting, was signed on November 11, 1918, in a railway car in Compi\u00e8gne, France.**\n    *   The official end of the war came with the signing of the **Treaty of Versailles** in June 1919. This treaty formally concluded the war between the Allies and Germany and imposed harsh terms on Germany, including territorial losses, reparations, and military restrictions. Separate treaties were signed with the other Central Powers.\n",
